Enable IPv6 dual protocol socket support on FreeBSD

It is possible to limit the jvm to default to IPv4 only sockets by
setting `java.net.preferIPv4Stack` to true. This is the default on
OpenBSD, but for otehr BSD's we follow the Java specification that
sockets should accept both IPv4 and IPv6 when the latter is available.

Sponsored by: The FreeBSD Foundation

Don't hide JVM symbols by default on FreeBSD

The symbols are needed for producing accurate stack traces for native
code. The way FreeBSD loads dynamic libs, and looks up symbols, it is
not able to find symbols that are marked as hidden (i.e. local.)

This patch changes the configuration for FreeBSD, so that the JVM will
be built with default symbol visibility.

This work was sponsored by: The FreeBSD Foundation

Fix symbol demangling on FreeBSD

To produce meaningful stack traces for native code, the JVM will try to
demangle symbols before presenting them. This makes C++ function names
appear as they do in the code with namespace and class names represented
properly.

To do this (on BSD's) it calls the system provided abi::__cxa_demangle
function. At least the FreeBSD implementation of this function will
return with a valid string containing garbage (but consistent carbage),
and a status of 0, if the origina symbol was _not_ mangled.

This patch adds a quick filter to ensure that only mangled symbols are
passed to the function. This ensures that the original symbol is
preserved in these cases.

This work was sponsored by: The FreeBSD Foundation

Fix mapping memory at specific address on FreeBSD

FreeBSD allows to specify the MAP_EXCL flag with MAP_FIXED, so that the
mapping will fail if any part of the region is already mapped. This is
consistent with the behaviour expected by OpenJDK.

This work was sponsored by: The FreeBSD Foundation

os/bsd: Make helper function private, and drop unused arg

This function is only used by the locally by the class itself, so
there's no reason to expose it externally. The unused mode arg, was
also dropped.

This work was sponsored by: The FreeBSD Foundation

The NodeGroup component has been enhanced with smooth animations and interactive states to improve user experience.

## Problem
The original NodeGroup component lacked visual feedback for user interactions:
- No animations when expanding/collapsing groups
- No visual indication when hovering over items
- No support for drag-and-drop visual states

## Solution
Added comprehensive animation and interaction support:

### Arrow Animation
- Smooth rotation from right (→) to up (↑) when expanding
- Uses CSS transforms with `0.15s ease-out` timing

### Content Animation  
- Smooth height and opacity transitions for expand/collapse
- Max-height animation with `0.3s ease-out` for smooth expansion
- Opacity fade with `0.15s ease-out` for content visibility

### Interactive Item States
- **Hover state**: Items show background color (`surfaceMid`) on mouse hover
- **Dragging state**: New `isDragging` prop applies 30% opacity and background color
- Smooth transitions for all state changes using theme animation values

## Implementation Details
- Fixed CSS transition syntax issues with theme duration values
- Used data attributes (`data-dragging`) for conditional styling
- Applied theme variables for consistent colors and timing
- Added comprehensive Storybook stories for testing all states

## Visual States

**Collapsed State** - Arrow points right, content hidden:
![NodeGroup Collapsed](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/086f531f-e204-4b4e-8727-64febd5b8573)

comment.body:
Commit b72bd63408cec659ee15b7869d5483d3f4b9a5ba brings Py-to-MATLAB conversion utilities for various datatypes.  I merged it for the time-being as I don't think I'll be working on this for a short while, but there is still a key point to address which is why I'll be keeping this issue open. This concerns input Data Representation for Save and Integrating with `scipy.io.savemat`.

Since bringing in different representations for MATLAB datatypes like `dictionary`, `containers.Map`, etc. its quite chaotic to manage differences between numpy types and others. Since I'm relying on `scipy.io.savemat` to actually write to file, this means trudging through a `dictionary` looking at each item. It might just be easier to write my own save method, which would simplify a lot of the case handling workflow. 

Some additional points:
- Haven't extensively tested the save methods with MATLAB datatypes
- timetable does not work in MATLAB
